{"ts":"2026-06-27T21:14:19.471Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Reviewing Initial Code Condition**\n\nI'm thrilled; the code passed linting with flying colors! Now, I'm shifting focus to a quick self-review, scrutinizing the design and implementation plan, especially regarding the user authentication narrative. I want to make sure we're on track with the planned modernization efforts.\n\n\n**Mapping Secure Data Structures**\n\nI'm now deeply engrossed in mapping out a DynamoDB table (`GFF_USERS`) to replace the memory stores. I'm focusing on a secure, scalable single-table design, and I'm really excited about showing clear role-based permissions and client isolation. This all comes to life as `gff_admin`, `client_admin`, and `client_member` entries. I'm taking special care to ensure the backend logic change is non-intrusive and doesn't affect the UI at all. This means my changes are focused on specific files: `lib/dynamodb-client.ts`, `app/api/v1/auth/login/route.ts`, and `app/api/v1/auth/me/route.ts`. The rest remain untouched. I'm also ensuring the JWT behavior from phase 5 stays the same.\n\n\n"}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T21:14:19.475Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"tool","toolName":"submit_and_exit","toolCallId":"yneq3w6m","input":{"summary":"Successfully completed the move of authentication users to DynamoDB (Phase 6 Auth).\n\n1. Installed `@aws-sdk/client-dynamodb` and `@aws-sdk/lib-dynamodb` to provide AWS DynamoDB connectivity in our TypeScript Next.js API endpoints.\n2. Installed `bcryptjs` and `@types/bcryptjs` to handle bcrypt secure password hashing and verification in TypeScript.\n3. Created `lib/dynamodb-client.ts` to construct a robust DynamoDB client connection. It fetches items from the `GFF_USERS` DynamoDB table, verifies password_hash (bcrypt) or local plain-text/SHA-256 fallback passwords, and maps roles ('gff_admin', 'client_admin', 'client_member') to correct clearances, client associations, and permissions.\n4. Updated `app/api/v1/auth/login/route.ts` to first query DynamoDB for user lookup and password verification, falling back gracefully to `API_MOCK_USERS` memory object if not found or if credentials are not configured.\n5. Updated `app/api/v1/auth/me/route.ts` to fetch the currently authenticated user details from DynamoDB first, falling back to mock users.\n6. Ran backend verification tests (`npm run backend:check`), local API test scripts (`node scripts/verify-auth-endpoints.js` and `node scripts/test-user-apis.js`), and checked code style via ESLint—all tests passed flawlessly with zero errors.","verified":true}}}
